        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-01-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1972-01-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="422"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d422">
                <head>422. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to Secretary
                    of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1" type="to">Rogers</persName>, Secretary of
                    Defense Laird, and Secretary of Commerce Stans<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d422fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1"
                            >RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970-73, <gloss target="#t_INCO1"
                            >INCO</gloss>-FISH <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>. Secret.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d422fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> informed <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_LMR2"
                            >Laird</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_SMH3">Stans</persName> that
                        President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> approved renewal of
                        Foreign Military Sales to Peru.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1972-01-14"
                        >January 14, 1972</date>.</dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>Foreign Military Sales Suspension Affecting Peru</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has studied the considerations and views set forth in your
                    Departments’ memoranda and has approved an approach to the Peruvian Government
                    including the following elements: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>An expression of appreciation for the restraint shown by the
                            Government of Peru during the past nine months.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The observation that the Foreign Military Sales suspension expires on
                            March 30, 1972.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>An invitation to the Government of Peru to begin immediate
                            consultations with us on the type of military equipment they wish to
                            acquire.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>The observation that if the Government of Peru were pre-pared to
                            indicate that the policy of restraint would be continued, the United
                            States Government would lift the Foreign Military Sales suspension
                            immediately.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
